# Checking for negative values in  Data columns

totalEntries = len(ConcreteData) # totalEntries - number of entries (rows) in the dataset

floatColumns = ['cement', 'slag', 'ash', 'water', 'superplastic', 'coarseagg',
       'fineagg', 'age', 'strength']
for col in floatColumns:
    count = 0;  # count - to keep track of numer of negative entries
    print('Column = ',col)  #pinting the current column
    for i in range(0,totalEntries):
       if (ConcreteData[col][i] < 0):    
            #print(BD[temp][i])
            count = count + 1
    print('Total number of Negative entries = ', count)
            

Column =  cement
Total number of Negative entries =  0

Visualization¶

Ingredients Distribution¶

In [20]:
import itertools

cols = [i for i in ConcreteData.columns if i not in 'strength']
length = len(cols)
cs = ["b","r","g","c","m","k","lime","c"]
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(13,25))

for i,j,k in itertools.zip_longest(cols,range(length),cs):
    plt.subplot(4,2,j+1)
    ax = sns.distplot(ConcreteData[i],color=k,rug=True)
    ax.set_facecolor("w")
    plt.axvline(ConcreteData[i].mean(),linestyle="dashed",label="mean",color="k")
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.title(i,color="navy")
    plt.xlabel("")

Swarm Plot For Variables¶

In [25]:
cols = ['cement', 'slag', 'ash', 'water', 'superplastic',
       'coarseagg', 'fineagg', 'age', 'strength'] 



length = len(cols)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,25))

for i,j in itertools.zip_longest(cols,range(length)):
    
    plt.subplot(3,3,j+1)
    ax = sns.swarmplot( y = ConcreteData[i],color="orange")
    ax.set_facecolor("k")
    ax.set_ylabel("")
    ax.set_title(i,color="navy")
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = .3)

Evaluate using KFold Cross Validation¶

In [89]:
#split the data
X_train_CV, X_test_CV, Y_train_CV, Y_test_CV = train_test_split(X_ConcreteData_scaled, Y_ConcreteData_scaled, test_size=0.30, random_state=1)


from sklearn import model_selection
seed = 6
kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=20, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

LR_model = LinearRegression()
CV_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(LR_model, X_ConcreteData_scaled, Y_ConcreteData_scaled, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=kfold)
print("Mean Square Error: %.3f (%.3f)" % (-CV_results.mean(), CV_results.std()))

#To get predictions (y_hat) and check them all in one using cross validation

predictions = cross_val_predict(LR_model, X_test_CV, Y_test_CV, cv = 5)     #y_test is needed here in predictions to get scores for each fold of cv
accuracy = metrics.r2_score(Y_test_CV, predictions)  #this says the accuracy of the predictions from the best cv fold
print("Accuracy R2score: %.3f" %accuracy)

Mean Square Error: 0.393 (0.078)
Accuracy R2score: 0.649
